"Hansen J., Sato M., Ruedy R., Lacis A., Oinas V.","Global warming in the twenty-first century: An alternative scenario",2000,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","97","18",,"9875","9880",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034730194&partnerID=40&md5=3064b0dfd9b66afc549a8e7007db4a9d","Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University Earth Institute, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Center for Environmental Prediction, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","Hansen, J., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Sato, M., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States, Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University Earth Institute, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Ruedy, R., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Lacis, A., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States; Oinas, V., Natl. Aero. and Space Administration, Goddard Institute for Space Studies, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States, Center for Environmental Prediction, Rutgers University, 2880 Broadway, New York, NY 10025, United States","A common view is that the current global warming rate will continue or accelerate. But we argue that rapid warming in recent decades has been driven mainly by non-CO2 greenhouse gases (GHGs), such as chlorofluorocarbons, CH4, and N2O, not by the products of fossil fuel burning, CO2 and aerosols, the positive and negative climate forcings of which are partially offsetting. The growth rate of non-CO2 GHGs has declined in the past decade. If sources of CH4 and O3 precursors were reduced in the future, the change in climate forcing by non-CO2 GHGs in the next 50 years could be near zero. Combined with a reduction of black carbon emissions and plausible success in slowing CO2 emissions, this reduction of non-CO2 GHGs could lead to a decline in the rate of global warming, reducing the danger of dramatic climate change. Such a focus on air pollution has practical benefits that unite the interests of developed and developing countries. However, assessment of ongoing and future climate change requires composition-specific long-term global monitoring of aerosol properties.","Aerosols; Air pollution; Climate change; Greenhouse gases","carbon dioxide; chlorofluorocarbon; methane; aerosol; air pollutant; air pollution; article; environmental temperature; global climate; greenhouse effect; priority journal; warming; Aerosols; Carbon Dioxide; Chlorofluorocarbons; Climate; Forecasting; Fossil Fuels; Greenhouse Effect; Methane; Models, Theoretical",,"Aerosols; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Chlorofluorocarbons; Fossil Fuels; Methane, 74-82-8",,,,"Hansen, J., Ruedy, R., Glascoe, J., Sato, M., (1999) J. Geophys. Res., 104, pp. 30997-31022; Jones, P.D., New, M., Parker, D.E., Martin, S., Rigor, I.G., (1999) Rev. Geophys., 37, pp. 173-199; Mann, M.E., Bradley, R.S., Hughes, M.K., (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett., 26, pp. 759-762; (1996) Climate Change 1995, , eds. Houghton J. T., Meira Filho, L. G., Callander, B. A., Harris, N., Kattenberg, A. & Maskell, K (Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U.K.); Hansen, J., Sato, M., Ruedy, R., (1997) J. Geophys. Res., 102, pp. 6831-6864; Hansen, J., Sato, M., Lacis, A., Ruedy, R., Tegen, I., Matthews, E., (1998) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 95, pp. 12753-12758; Levitus, S., Ant